That error usually means the compiler doesn’t know what vector is, or something in the file is shadowing the name vector. In practice it comes from one of these three causes.

1️⃣ Missing <vector> header (most common)

C++ won’t recognize std::vector unless you include the header.

Make sure the top of your file has:

C++
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
#include <stack>

And then either use:

C++
std::vector<Point> points;

or

C++
using namespace std;
vector<Point> points;

If <vector> is missing you’ll get errors like:

vector is not a template
2️⃣ You accidentally created a variable named vector

Example mistake:

C++
int vector = 5;

Then later:

C++
vector<Point> points;

Now the compiler thinks vector is an integer, not std::vector.

Search your file for something like:

vector =

or

int vector

and remove it.

3️⃣ Using vector without std::

If you removed using namespace std;, then you must write:

C++
std::vector<Point> points;
std::vector<Point> hull;
Safe Professional Fix (Recommended)

Avoid namespace pollution.

Change these lines:

C++
vector<Point> points;
vector<Point> hull;

to

C++
std::vector<Point> points;
std::vector<Point> hull;

And ensure headers exist:

C++
#include <vector>
#include <stack>
#include <algorithm>
Quick sanity check

Your file header should look like this:

C++
#include <SFML/Graphics.hpp>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
#include <stack>
#include <cmath>
If the error still persists

Paste the first 40 lines of your code, because that error almost always means:

header missing

namespace issue

variable named vector

One look and it’s immediately fixable.

